E. In some cases hiatus may be due, partly or entirely, to the influence on pronunciation of the lost ablative-ending -d.

(a) In the case of me and te the old pronunciation still lingered on in Plautus’s time 3 accordingly hiatus frequently occurs after them in his plays, though chiefly at a break in metre or sense (many instances have been noted under C and D) 3 when hiatus follows them elsewhere, me, te are printed med, led in the present text. The accusatives of these pronouns are by false analogy treated in the same way.
